Conservation laws, symmetries, and line soliton
solutions of generalized KP and Boussinesq
equations with pğ‘p-power nonlinearities
in two dimensions

S.C. Anco1, M.L. Gandarias2, E. Recio2
1Brock University, St Catharines Canada
2Cadiz University, Cadiz Spain
Abstract

Nonlinear generalizations of integrable equations in one dimension, such as the KdV and Boussinesq equations with pğ‘p-power nonlinearities, arise in many physical applications and are interesting in analysis due to critical behaviour. This paper studies analogous nonlinear pğ‘p-power generalizations of the integrable KP equation and the Boussinesq equation in two dimensions. Several results are obtained. First, for all pâ‰ 0ğ‘0p\neq 0, a Hamiltonian formulation of both generalized equations is given. Second, all Lie symmetries are derived, including any that exist for special powers pâ‰ 0ğ‘0p\neq 0. Third, Noetherâ€™s theorem is applied to obtain the conservation laws arising from the Lie symmetries that are variational. Finally, explicit line soliton solutions are derived for all powers p>0ğ‘0p>0, and some of their properties are discussed.

The purpose of the present paper is to determine the conservation laws, symmetries, and line soliton solutions admitted by the gKP equation (3) and the 2D gB equation (4) in 2+1212+1 dimensions, for all nonlinearity powers p>0ğ‘0p>0.

First, in sectionÂ 2, both the gKP and 2D gB equations for arbitrary pâ‰ 0ğ‘0p\neq 0 are formulated as Hamiltonian systems by the introduction of potentials. Next, all Lie point symmetries are obtained in sectionÂ 3, and the class of variational point symmetries is found. Through Noetherâ€™s theorem in the Hamiltonian setting, the corresponding conservation laws are derived in sectionÂ 4. These results include any point symmetries and any Noether conservation laws that arise for special powers pâ‰ 0ğ‘0p\neq 0.

In sectionÂ 5, line solitons u=Uâ€‹(x+Î¼â€‹yâˆ’Î½â€‹t)ğ‘¢ğ‘ˆğ‘¥ğœ‡ğ‘¦ğœˆğ‘¡u=U(x+\mu y-\nu t) are considered for both the gKP and 2D gB equations for all p>0ğ‘0p>0, where the parameters Î¼ğœ‡\mu and Î½ğœˆ\nu determine the direction and the speed of the line soliton. The resulting fourth-order nonlinear differential equations for Uğ‘ˆU are directly reduced to first-order separable differential equations by use of the conservation laws obtained for the gKP and 2D gB equations. These separable differential equations are then integrated to get the explicit form of the line soliton solutions for all p>0ğ‘0p>0, with Î¼ğœ‡\mu and cğ‘c being arbitrary apart from satisfying a kinematic inequality. Some properties of these solutions are discussed.

Finally, a few concluding remarks are made in sectionÂ 6.

A few conservation laws of the gKP equation (3) in the case p=2ğ‘2p=2 and the 2D gB equation (4) in the case p=2ğ‘2p=2 have been found previously in Refs.[18, 21]. Some solutions of the gKP equation in three dimensions, without any discussion of their properties, are obtained in Ref.[2] A general treatment of symmetries, conservation laws, and their applications to differential equations can be found in Refs.[20, 7].

3 Symmetries

4 Conservation laws

Conservation laws are of basic importance for nonlinear evolution equations because, for all solutions, they provide physical, conserved quantities as well as conserved norms

6 Concluding remarks

For the generalized KP equation (3) and the 2D generalized Boussinesq equation (4) with pğ‘p-power nonlinearities, we have derived all conservation laws that arise from variational point symmetries and used them to obtain the general line soliton solutions of these two equations for all powers p>0ğ‘0p>0. We have also discussed some basic kinematical properties of the line solitons.

Our results can be further used as a starting point to investigate the stability of the line soliton solutions for the gKP equation. It is known that [13, 19] the line solitons of the KP equation (p=1ğ‘1p=1) are stable in the case Ïƒ2=1superscriptğœ21\sigma^{2}=1 and unstable in the opposite case Ïƒ2=âˆ’1superscriptğœ21\sigma^{2}=-1. An interesting question is to determine the stability of the line solitons for higher powers pâ‰¥2ğ‘2p\geq 2. Compared to the KdV equation, in two dimensions the critical power for the conserved mass is p=43ğ‘43p=\tfrac{4}{3}, while the critical power for the conserved energy is p=4ğ‘4p=4.

In addition to line soliton solutions, the KP equation possesses lump solutions, which are rational functions and involve several parameters. No lump solutions are known for the modified KP equation, and an interesting question is to see if a similar result will hold for the gKP equation for all p>1ğ‘1p>1.

Stability of line solitons and existence of lump solutions can be investigated similarly for the 2D gB equation.
